3. Visualize different columns¶

A. Drawing a simple density plot with default parameters¶

In [23]:
# Make default density plot
sns.kdeplot(df['sepal_width'])
plt.show()

B. Improving the graph with different parameters¶

  • Specify the data and the x-variable.
  • Set the color of the line.
  • Add a label for the legend.
  • Set the linewidth.
  • Adjust the transparency.
  • fill: If True, the area under the KDE curve is filled with the specified color.
  • Change the y-axis to density.
  • Add a title and axis labels.
  • Show the legend.
In [27]:
# Create the Density plot
sns.kdeplot(
    data=df,
    x="sepal_length",
    color="red",
    label="Sepal Length",
    linewidth=2,  # Line thickness
    alpha=0.7,      # Transparency
    fill=True,     # Fill the area under the curve
)

plt.title("Sepal Length Density Plot")
plt.xlabel("Sepal Length (cm)")
plt.ylabel("Density")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

C. Visualize multiple density plots together¶

  1. Define the columns to plot ( update based on your scenario )
  2. Define the colors of each density plot ( update based on your choice/preference )
  3. we created a 2 * 2 matrix with each figure as (14 , 10 ) , you can update each of them based on preference
In [28]:
# Define the columns to plot
columns_to_plot = ['sepal_length', 'sepal_width', 'petal_length', 'petal_width']

# Define colors for each density plot
colors = ['red', 'green', 'orange', 'coral']  # Add more colors if needed

# Create a 2x2 subplot grid with a fixed figure size
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(14, 10))

# Iterate through the columns and plot each one in a separate subplot
for i, col in enumerate(columns_to_plot):
    # Determine the row and column for the current subplot
    row = i // 2
    col_num = i % 2

    # Select the appropriate subplot axis
    ax = axes[row, col_num]

    # Create the density plot , using a different color for each
    sns.kdeplot(data=df, x=col, color=colors[i], label=col, linewidth=2, alpha=0.7, fill="True", ax=ax)

    # Set the title and labels for the subplot
    ax.set_title(f"{col.title()} Distribution")
    ax.set_xlabel(f"{col.title()} (cm)")
    ax.set_ylabel("Density")
    ax.legend()

# Adjust the layout to prevent overlapping titles/labels
plt.tight_layout()

# Display the plots
plt.show()

4. How to Interpret Density plot :¶

Key Features to Look For

Shape:

  • Symmetric: The left and right sides of the curve are roughly mirror images.
  • Skewed: The curve has a "tail" extending more to one side.
    • Right-skewed (positive skew): The tail extends to the right.
    • Left-skewed (negative skew): The tail extends to the left.
  • Unimodal: The curve has one peak.
  • Bimodal: The curve has two peaks.
  • Multimodal: The curve has more than two peaks.

Center: Where is the data concentrated? Look for the peak of the curve, which gives you an idea of the typical value (similar to the mode in a histogram).

Spread: How much does the data vary?

  • Narrow curve: Data points are clustered close together.
  • Wide curve: Data points are more spread out.

Outliers: Density plots don't show outliers as explicitly as histograms, but outliers can influence the shape of the tail of the curve. A long tail in one direction might suggest the presence of outliers.

Gaps: Density plots, by their nature, create a continuous curve, so they don't show gaps in the same way histograms do. However, very low-density regions might hint at a sparsity of data in those intervals.

  1. Sepal Length Distribution
  • Shape: Slightly right-skewed.
  • Center: The data is concentrated around 5.5 cm.
  • Spread: The curve has a moderate spread, ranging from around 4 cm to 8 cm.
  • Outliers: The rightward tail suggests the presence of potential outliers, though not very pronounced.
  • Gaps: No significant gaps.
  1. Sepal Width Distribution
  • Shape: Nearly symmetric.
  • Center: The data is concentrated around 3 cm.
  • Spread: The curve has a narrow spread, ranging from around 2 cm to 4 cm.
  • Outliers: No significant outliers.
  • Gaps: No significant gaps.
  1. Petal Length Distribution
  • Shape: Bimodal, with peaks around 1.5 cm and 4.5 cm.
  • Center: The data has two centers of concentration.
  • Spread: The curve has a wide spread, ranging from around 1 cm to 7 cm.
  • Outliers: The curve extends to the right, suggesting possible outliers.
  • Gaps: The bimodality suggests a low-density region between the two peaks.
  1. Petal Width Distribution
  • Shape: Right-skewed, with a major peak at around 0.25 and a minor peak at around 1.3.
  • Center: The data is concentrated around 0.25 cm, with a secondary concentration at around 1.3 cm.
  • Spread: The curve has a moderate spread, ranging from around 0 cm to 2.5 cm.
  • Outliers: The curve extends to the right, suggesting possible outliers.
  • Gaps: The shape indicates a sparsity of data between the two peaks.

# Make default cumulative density plot
sns.kdeplot(df['sepal_width'], cumulative=True)
plt.show()

B. Improving the graph with different parameters¶

  • Specify the data and the x-variable.
  • Set the color of the line.
  • Add a label for the legend.
  • Set the linewidth.
  • Adjust the transparency.
  • Add a title and axis labels.

In [30]:
# Create the cumulative density plot
sns.kdeplot(
    data=df,
    x="sepal_length",
    cumulative=True,  # Key parameter:  Make it cumulative
    color="red",
    label="Sepal Length CDF",
    linewidth=2,
    alpha=0.7,
    linestyle='-',  # Line style
)

plt.title("Cumulative Distribution of Sepal Length")
plt.xlabel("Sepal Length (cm)")
plt.ylabel("Cumulative Probability")  # Changed y-axis label
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)  # Add gridlines for better readability
plt.show()

C. Visualize multiple density plots together¶

  • Define the columns to plot ( update based on your scenario )
  • Define the colors of each cumulative density plot ( update based on your choice/preference )
  • we created a 2 * 2 matrix with each figure as (14 , 10 ) , you can update each of them based on preference
In [34]:
# Define the columns to plot
columns_to_plot = ['sepal_length', 'sepal_width', 'petal_length', 'petal_width']

# Define colors for each density plot
colors = ['red', 'green', 'orange', 'coral']  # Add more colors if needed

# Create a 2x2 subplot grid with a fixed figure size
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(14, 10))

# Iterate through the columns and plot each one in a separate subplot
for i, col in enumerate(columns_to_plot):
    # Determine the row and column for the current subplot
    row = i // 2
    col_num = i % 2

    # Select the appropriate subplot axis
    ax = axes[row, col_num]

    # Create the cumulative density plot, using a different color for each
    sns.kdeplot(data=df, x=col, color=colors[i], label=col, cumulative=True , linewidth=2, alpha=0.7, linestyle='-', ax=ax)

    # Set the title and labels for the subplot
    ax.set_title(f"{col.title()} Cumulative Distribution")
    ax.set_xlabel(f"{col.title()} (cm)")
    ax.set_ylabel("Density")
    ax.legend()

# Adjust the layout to prevent overlapping titles/labels
plt.tight_layout()

# Display the plots
plt.show()

6. How to Interpret Cumulative Density plot :¶

Key Features to Look For

Shape:

  • A CDF always starts at 0 on the y-axis and increases to 1. It shows how the cumulative probability grows as the variable's value increases.
  • Symmetric/Skewed: These terms don't apply to CDFs in the same way as they do to regular density plots or histograms. A CDF shows the accumulation of probability, not the shape of the distribution itself. However, you can infer skewness from the CDF's steepness:
  • If the CDF rises quickly initially and then levels off slowly, it indicates a right-skewed distribution.
  • If the CDF rises slowly initially and then steepens, it indicates a left-skewed distribution.
  • Unimodal/Bimodal/Multimodal: These terms don't directly apply to CDFs. A CDF will show a smooth, increasing curve, even if the underlying distribution is multimodal. The steepness of the CDF can give you an idea where the modes of the distribution are.

Center:

  • The "center" is represented by the value on the x-axis where the CDF reaches 0.5 (50%). This point corresponds to the median of the data.

Spread:

  • The spread is indicated by the steepness of the CDF curve.
    • A steep CDF indicates a narrow spread (data points are concentrated).
    • A gradual CDF indicates a wide spread (data points are more dispersed).

Outliers:

  • Outliers can be inferred from the CDF. If the CDF curve increases very slowly at the extreme ends of the x-axis, it suggests the presence of potential outliers.

Gaps:

  • CDFs don't directly show gaps in the data in the same way histograms do. However, a long, flat section in the CDF might suggest a range of values where there are few data points.

In summary, a CDF shows the probability that a data point is less than or equal to a given value. You can use it to understand the median, spread, and skewness of the data.

  1. Sepal Length Cumulative Distribution
  • Shape: The CDF starts at 0 and rises steadily to 1. It increases more rapidly in the approximate range of 5 to 6 cm, then levels off. This indicates that a large proportion of the data falls within this range.
  • Center: The median sepal length (where the CDF reaches 0.5) is around 5.8 cm.
  • Spread: The CDF rises fairly steeply, indicating a relatively narrow spread of data. Most of the sepal lengths are clustered relatively close to the median.
  • Skewness: The CDF rises quickly initially and then levels off slowly, which indicates a slight rightward skew in the distribution of sepal lengths.
  • Outliers: The CDF approaches 0 slowly on the left and 1 slowly on the right, suggesting that there might be a few sepal lengths that are considerably shorter or longer than the majority, but their influence is not very strong.
  • Gaps: CDFs don't directly show gaps.
  1. Sepal Width Cumulative Distribution
  • Shape: The CDF starts at 0 and rises steeply to 1. The rise is concentrated in the 2.5 to 3.5 cm range.
  • Center: The median sepal width is approximately 3.0 cm.
  • Spread: The CDF is steep, indicating a narrow spread. Sepal widths are concentrated around the median.
  • Skewness: The CDF rises quickly and levels off somewhat symmetrically, suggesting a roughly symmetrical distribution of sepal widths.
  • Outliers: The CDF approaches 0 and 1 quickly, indicating that there are few extreme values.
  • Gaps: CDFs don't directly show gaps.
  1. Petal Length Cumulative Distribution
  • Shape: The CDF starts at 0 and rises to 1, but its rise is not as smooth. There are two regions where the CDF increases more rapidly: one between 1 and 2 cm and another between 4 and 5 cm. This corresponds to the two peaks in the petal length distribution.
  • Center: The median petal length is around 4 cm.
  • Spread: The CDF has a wider spread than sepal width, indicating greater variability in petal lengths.
  • Skewness: The CDF rises slowly initially, then more quickly, and then levels off, suggesting a rightward skew.
  • Outliers: The CDF reaches 1 slowly, suggesting the presence of longer petal lengths.
  • Gaps: CDFs don't directly show gaps, but the change in steepness hints at the bimodality seen in the petal length distribution.
  1. Petal Width Cumulative Distribution
  • Shape: The CDF starts at 0 and rises to 1, with a rapid increase between 0 to 0.5 cm and another increase between 1 and 1.5 cm.
  • Center: The median petal width is around 1.3 cm.
  • Spread: The CDF shows a moderate spread.
  • Skewness: The CDF rises slowly initially and then steepens, indicating a rightward skew.
  • Outliers: The CDF approaches 1 gradually, indicating the presence of some wider petal widths, though not very extreme.
  • Gaps: CDFs don't directly show gaps, but the varying steepness suggests the underlying distribution has multiple modes.

7. Example Business questions that can be answered by cumulative density plot¶

Here are some examples of business questions that can be answered using cumulative density plots:

Customer/Market Analysis:

  • "What percentage of our customers spend less than $X per transaction?"
  • "What is the distribution of customer ages, and what proportion falls within specific age brackets (e.g., under 25, between 25 and 40)?"
  • "What proportion of website visitors spend less than Y minutes on the site?"
  • "What is the cumulative distribution of customer income, and what percentage of our customer base earns above a certain threshold?"
  • "How does customer spending behavior compare between different marketing campaigns?"

Sales and Revenue:

  • "What proportion of sales falls below a certain revenue target?"
  • "What is the distribution of sales cycle lengths, and what percentage of sales close within a specific timeframe?"
  • "What percentage of products account for less than Z% of total revenue (Pareto analysis)?"

Risk Management:

  • "What is the cumulative distribution of loan defaults, and what percentage of loans have a default rate below a certain level?"
  • "What is the distribution of insurance claim amounts, and what percentage of claims are below a certain value?"
  • "What is the cumulative probability of project cost overruns?"

Operations and Supply Chain:

  • "What is the distribution of delivery times, and what percentage of orders are delivered within the promised timeframe?"
  • "What is the cumulative distribution of production defect rates?"
  • "What is the distribution of inventory levels, and what percentage of time is inventory below a critical threshold?"

Human Resources:

  • "What is the distribution of employee salaries, and what percentage of employees earn less than a certain amount?"
  • "What is the distribution of employee tenure, and what percentage of employees have been with the company for more than X years?"
  • “What percentage of employees are below a certain performance level?”
